nstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0},{"place":"Half Moon","mileFromStart":6.8,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.81956,"lng":-83.62139,"seq":6,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0},{"place":"Hansen's Point","mileFromStart":6.8,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.81661,"lng":-83.62661,"seq":7,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.4},{"place":"Princess Arch","mileFromStart":7.2,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.82735,"lng":-83.61966,"seq":8,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":1.1},{"place":"Adena Arch","mileFromStart":8.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.83913,"lng":-83.61227,"seq":9,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.9},{"place":"Bell Falls","mileFromStart":9.2,"kind":"crossing","lat":37.83138,"lng":-83.60215,"seq":10,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":1.2},{"place":"Buzzard's Roost","mileFromStart":10.4,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.81696,"lng":-83.58857,"seq":11,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":1.5},{"place":"Olivia Addison Falls","mileFromStart":11.9,"kind":"crossing","lat":37.82509,"lng":-83.57068,"seq":12,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.3},{"place":"Lower Sky Bridge Ridge","mileFromStart":12.2,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.81866,"lng":-83.57756,"seq":13,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":1.1},{"place":"Scenic overlook","mileFromStart":13.3,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.81017,"lng":-83.5925,"seq":14,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":0.9},{"place":"Angel Windows","mileFromStart":14.2,"kind":"overlook","lat":37.79991,"lng":-83.59267,"seq":15,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"","toNextMi":19.8},{"place":"Black River (end)","mileFromStart":34,"kind":"terminus","lat":37.70627,"lng":-83.67627,"seq":16,"src":"openstreetmap","control":[],"note":"The drive ends here"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["According to the surveys of William A. Burt in 1848, a wagon road ran south from the modern site of the Black River Harbor to Chippewa Hill, the location of Copper Peak. A wagon road was built by the State of Michigan in 1904 to connect the waterfront with Bessemer. The county had purchased the land around the waterfront in 1924 for a park, and a county road running parallel to the Black River was in place by 1927. The residents of the fishing village were forced to move and settled at Black River Village. The roadway was improved to a gravel surface by 1930, and fully paved in late 1949 or early 1950. In 1967, the Gogebic County exchanged the park land along the river, including the harbor, with the USFS for other land in the area, and the harbor has been under federal maintenance since. Local officials originally proposed the National Forest Scenic Byway designation for the road in April 1991. The desire was to \"showcase a special part of the National Forest\" and boost tourism to the area, according to the park ranger in charge of handling the application. The designation was conferred by the USFS on June 20, 1992, with a dedication ceremony on September 19 that year."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"Michigan Department of Transportation (2021). Next Generation PR Finder (Map). Michigan Department of Transportation. Retrieved October 11, 2021.","url":"https://mdotgis.state.mi.us/portal/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=c3aa2462a1e24e37a33184a33e5976aa"},{"n":2,"text":"Levra, Margaret (September 21, 1992). \"Scenic Byway Dedicated\". Ironwood Daily Globe. pp. 1, 12. OCLC 10890811. Retrieved August 11, 2018 – via NewspaperArchive.com.","url":"https://newspaperarchive.com/michael-g-other-articles-clipping-sep-21-1992-784447"},{"n":3,"text":"Federal Highway Administration (n.d.). \"Black River Scenic Byway\" (Map). America's Byways. Federal Highway Administration. Archived from the original on June 22, 2013. Retrieved May 14, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20130622055728/http://byways.org/explore/byways/10780/travel.html"},{"n":4,"text":"\"Overview Map of the Black River National Forest Scenic Byway\" (Map). Google Maps. Retrieved May 14, 2012.","url":"https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=Unknown+road&daddr=Black+River+Rd%2FBlack+River+Harbor+Pkwy&hl=en&sll=46.658745,-90.043302&sspn=0.028394,0.02914&geocode=FbwPyAIddPih-g%3BFSLZxQIdpjuh-g&oq=Black+River+Harbor&t=h&mra=ls&z=12"},{"n":5,"text":"Orbitz Away (September 15, 2010). \"Ottawa National Forest: Scenic Driving (part 8 of 9)\". Gorp: Great Outdoor Recreation Pages. Orbitz Away. Archived from the original on May 18, 2011. Retrieved June 14, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20110518010401/http://www.gorp.com/parks-guide/travel-ta-ottawa-national-forest-scenic-drives-ironwood-sidwcmdev_066216.html"},{"n":6,"text":"Palm Partnership Training (n.d.). \"Royal Palm Ranch\". Palm Partnership Training. Archived from the original on August 19, 2012. Retrieved June 25, 2012.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20120819115103/http://www.lynnpalm.com/michigan.html"},{"n":7,"text":"Murray, Dave (September 6, 2011). \"Bad Postcards: Copper Peak Operators Promise Their Ski Flying Hill Is More impressive than Card Depicts\". The Grand Rapids Press. OCLC 9975013. Archived from the original on July 12, 2014. Retrieved June 14, 2012.","url":"http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2011/09/bad_psotcards_copper_peak_oper.html"},{"n":8,"text":"Hunt, Mary & Hunt, Don (2011). \"Bessemer: Copper Peak Ski Flying Hill\". Hunts' Guide to Michigan's Upper Peninsula. Albion, MI: Midwestern Guides. Retrieved June 14, 2012.","url":"http://hunts-upguide.com/bessemer_copper_peak_ski_flying_hill.html"}],"routeLine":[[37.81477,-83.71884],[37.8152,-83.71824],[37.81534,-83.71729],[37.81548,-83.7165],[37.81624,-83.71525],[37.81657,-83.71449],[37.81662,-83.71354],[37.81652,-83.71277],[37.81633,-83.71192],[37.81601,-83.71117],[37.81567,-83.71056],[37.81569,-83.70967],[37.81575,-83.70891],[37.81562,-83.7081],[37.8152,-83.70728],[37.8